observations.recommendation:
We recommended and the Management agreed that:

Management conduct physical inventory of the land

Management maintain property and subsidiary ledger cards and prepare/reconcile same with the Report on Physical Count of PPE;

Management appropriate fund for the titling of all land;

The LCE direct the Municipal Assessor’s Office to exert effort in titling the land owned by the Municipality.

We recommended and Management agreed to the following:
Mobilize additional competent personnel from other departments as members and completely conduct physical count of Inventory of the Municipality’s PPE annually and submit to the Office of the Auditor the duly accomplished RPCPPE of all PPE accounts;
To direct the Municipal Accountant and designated General Services Officer reconcile and analyze the difference between ledger and RPCPPE report and effect necessary adjustments;
Instruct the General Services Office to transfer all identified unserviceable properties in the Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Property Form as prescribed in Annex 51, Volume 2 of the Manual on the NGAS for LGUs, for proper disposal and basis to derecognize from the book of accounts, then undertake necessary actions for disposal in accordance with Section 79 of PD 1445;
Require the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Designate GSO maintain Property, Plant and Equipment Ledger Cards (PPELC) and Property Cards for each group of PPEs, respectively and reconciliation between these two records shall be undertaken regularly; and
In response to COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020 and EO No. 2023-32, conduct one-time cleansing of the Municipality’s PPE to establish PPE balances that are verifiable as to existence, condition and accountability.

We recommended that:
7.Management conduct physical inventory of the land


8.Management maintain property and subsidiary ledger cards and prepare/reconcile same with the Report on Physical Count of PPE;


9.Management appropriate fund for the titling of all land;




10.The LCE direct the Municipal Assessor’s Office to exert effort in titling the land owned by the Municipality.

We reiterated our recommendation that the Municipal Mayor instruct the:
a. MGSO-Designate and members of the Inventory Committee to cause the determination of all the properties of the Municipality that are unserviceable, obsolete and/or no longer needed and prepare the IIRUP;
b. MGSO-Designate and Disposal Committee to prepare a timeline for immediate disposal of unserviceable and obsolete properties to avoid further deterioration and/or wastage and unnecessary consumption of storage space;
c. MGSO-Designate and the Municipal Accountant to update their respective records for the unserviceable properties to facilitate reconciliation of records, prior to disposal; and
d. Municipal Accountant to disclose in the Notes to Financial Statements the details of properties due for disposal and those which are fully depreciated but are still in use by the Municipality for fairly presented PPE balances.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the:
a. Municipal Agriculturist to submit a valid explanation on the non-monitoring of the distributed cattle covered by Balete Livestock Dispersal Program which led to the sale and death of cattle with undetermined amount;
b. Municipal Agriculturist to immediately conduct thorough investigation and prepare the reports regarding the sale of 31 cattle and death of three, considering the stipulations incorporated in the Contract Agreement, and file the necessary request for relief from accountability over the death of the cattle;
c. Municipal Agriculturist to update and maintain complete records for each beneficiary of the cattle to properly monitor custodianship and assess whether the objectives of the Program have been achieved or there is a need to revisit/amend the Program itself to attain a desirable and realizable result;
d. Property Officer to undertake the physical inventory of the cattle regularly and prepare and submit the required Inventory report thereof; and
e. Municipal Accountant to prepare the WOABSLC for each cattle under the Program.
We also recommended strict compliance with the provisions of Section 73(1) of PD No. 1445 and Section 151 of COA Circular No. 92-386.

Mobilize additional competent personnel from other departments as members and completely conduct physical count of Inventory of the Municipality’s PPE annually and submit to the Office of the Auditor the duly accomplished RPCPPE of all PPE accounts;
Direct the Municipal Accountant and Designate General Services Officer reconcile and analyze the difference between ledger and RPCPPE and effect necessary adjustments;
Instruct the General Services Office to prepare and transfer all identified unserviceable properties in the Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Property (IIRUP) Form as prescribed in Annex 51, Volume 2 of the Manual on the NGAS for LGUs, for proper disposal and basis to derecognize from the book of accounts, then undertake necessary actions for disposal in accordance with Section 79 of PD 1445;
Require the Municipal Accountant and the Designate GSO maintain Property, Plant and Equipment Ledger Cards (PPELC) and Property Cards for each group of PPEs, respectively and reconciliation between these two records shall be undertaken regularly; and
In response to COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020, create an Inventory Committee for the sole purpose of conducting a one-time cleansing of the Municipality’s PPE which shall be composed of adequate number of members to be able to complete the physical inventory.

Require the MPDO and Municipal Engineer to properly plan the programs/projects by addressing first issues related to its implementation and if readily implementable the within prescribed timeline to avoid such delay in the implementation in the future;
Require the MPDO and Municipal Engineer to have a close-in monitoring and supervision on the project and provide accurate report. As a case maybe, impose upon to the contractor in default the liquidated damages an amount to at least one tenth (1/10) of one percent of the cost of the unperformed portion of the works for every day of delay from the contract duration expires, including any time extension duly granted; and
Cause the immediate completion of the Project.

Require the Municipal Engineer to prepare the pre-evaluation report with sufficient details, the scope of work and secure a copy of documents indicating the history of repair before the conduct of pre-repair inspection report of the equipment and vehicle subject for repair;
Require the preparation of Waste Material Reports of the damaged replaced part and have is inspected before disposal is made; and
The Municipal Accountant cautiously check the completeness of all the pertinent supporting documents before allowing the payment.

We recommended that:

1.Management conduct physical inventory of the land; 

2.Management maintain property and subsidiary ledger cards and prepare/reconcile same with the Report on Physical Count of PPE;

3.Management appropriate fund for the titling of all land;

4.The LCE direct the Municipal Assessor’s Office to exert effort in titling the land owned by the Municipality;

We recommended the following:

The Inventory Committee conduct physical inventory of the Municipality’s PPE annually and submit to the Office of the Auditor the duly accomplished RPCPPE not later than January 31 of the following year;

The inventory taking shall be per PPE account/each category of assets and prepare the RPCPPE on the result thereof in conformity with the above-mentioned Manual for LGUs;

The accounting office and designated General Services Officer religiously maintain the PPELC and Stock Cards/Property Cards; and

The Accounting office and General Services Office reconcile PPE accounts between PPELC and Property Cards.

We recommended that:

a)	The inventory taking shall be done by office and prepare the corresponding RPCPPE on   the results thereof, and;

b)	The RPCPPE shall then be reconciled with accounting records in order to ensure that PPE account balances in the financial statements are fairly presented.

